"## Abstract\nLight field depth estimation is crucial for 3D vision, yet accurately estimating depth on non-Lambertian surfaces remains a formidable challenge. Conventional epipolar plane image (EPI) methods rely on linear slope assumptions, which fundamentally fail when physical reflectance properties like specularities disrupt angular coherence in low-resolution light fields. To address this, we proposed a unified dual-mask physical model that decoupled environmental illumination, parallax, and material reflectance via a novel three-layer angular signal decomposition. Specifically, we extracted geometric angular features, such as angular gradients, to generate precise pixel-level Lambertian and non-Lambertian masks using a random forest classifier. These dual masks guided a dual-branch network for adaptive feature routing and depth regression. Furthermore, we employed a progressive training strategy integrated with domain-balanced sampling and guided training to overcome data scarcity and distribution shifts across heterogeneous domains. Extensive experiments demonstrate that our mask generation achieves an accuracy of 89.6% and an AUC of 0.962. The proposed model yields an overall mean absolute error (MAE) of 0.133 and significantly reduces the MAE to 0.081 in complex mixed urban scenarios, outperforming existing baselines. Ultimately, this work provides a robust physical prior for light field depth estimation, substantially enhancing generalization and tolerance in real-world scenes with mixed materials.\n\n**Keywords:** Light field depth estimation, Non-Lambertian reflection, Angular signal decomposition, Dual-mask routing, Epipolar plane image, Progressive training"